NAME: One year with antidepressants
HOST: Journal
BREF: I've been taking antidepressants for a year now, and I wanted to write a kind of testify about what it was.
PRIV: false
MENU: true
BODY:

# Antidepressants can't change the world, but they made it tolerable for me

I've been taking antidepressants for a year now, and I wanted to write a kind of note about how it went. France is known for prescribing a lot of antidepressants, and it's often seen as a kind of morale or motivational failure ("Man up!") that can or should be fixed with a rest ("Go to the beach!").

As a result, the first time I talked about it, my partner was suddenly alarmed. We were out of the first Covid lockdown in France, and it seemed I was doing better after I broke two months prior. Or, should I say, the work of _re-sensibilization_ I was gradually doing with my therapist (allowing myself to listen to my physical and mental sensations) broke loose. The dam that was preventing the feels to overflow me broke, and it took quite some time for everything to settle down.

So two months later, I didn't know what my profesionnal future was going to be, I was buying an apartment, I could not see my therapist to talk about all this. Nor do I wanted to see my therapist. I had already told her I was fed up with fighting for control, that I wanted the _easy mode_ for a moment. So, in a very pragmatic approach, I wrote down on paper what I was feeling and went to see my doctor, and read in front of her what I had written.

Overall, my symptoms were:

- An inabiliby to manage unexpected problems. Even the smallest ones took gigantic proportions, made me feel overwhelmed and created panic crisis.
- Fatigue. Fortunately, not a massive fatigue that made me unable to socialize. But just getting up in the morning was a chore.
- The inabiliby to focus on mentally uncomfortable tasks. It made starting new things very difficult.
- Physical pain in the neck, but not entirely due to work desk. My muscles were getting tense for no reasons during conversations.
- A feeling of a fear that everything could suddenly collapse. Like, as if something catastrophic was about to happen. It was not very conscious, it just manifested every so often.

And so, because of all the uncertainties related to my career and all the work that was coming with the apartment that I didn't know how to handle, I suggested I could, maybe, start taking antidepressants. She agreed and, seeing it was more an anxious depressive disorder than a fully fledged depression, decided to give me a very mild one dosage.

It turned out to be a very nice move from her. It removed almost all the symptoms I listed earlier, but didn't make me dull, more tired or unable to feel. As a result, I have never felt so good in years. I have never felt so _myself_. Turns out it wasn't just a feeling. My partner said something that really touched me, she said she felt I was _more like the old me, the one when we met_.

As a result, I've made considerable progress on many things in the last year. I'm more focused, anxiety and physical pain are gone, as well as the feeling of catastrophe. The considerable amount of work I did in my apartment made me extremely more relaxed about maintaining unexpected problems too.

Today, after renewing my prescription, my doctor talked to me about the future. Am I ready to stop taking antidepressants? At the moment, no. I don't even want to, as I am making huge progress into discovering myself, at the right pace. A moment will inevitably come, when I will have to stop, but... _waves at everything bad that is currently happening in the world_.

Anyway, that's my personal testimony about taking antidepressants. Please don't take it as a medical advice. Antidepressants are not a magic pill, it's just that *for me*, they worked and since there's a stigma around them, I wanted to encourage people that have the same symptoms as me to, maybe, try talking about them with their doctor, and see how it goes from there.

Take care.


====

NAME: Characters
HOST: Projects
BREF: Character design
PRIV: true
MENU: true
BODY:

# Character design

Character design notes for a project.

## Main char no name

Physical attributes:

- Rather small by the standards of the cast, and so she has more body shapes than most flower gatherers that were once women, even if it's not much. Most flower gatherers are taller than other people due to the sap in their body. Due to malnutrition during her youth that prevented a normal growth, she is as tall as a standard tall man.
- When not prepared for a long trip, rather thin yet always muscular due to sustained physical activity. Takes more body weight and gets more square physically when preparing for long trips, with hips and waist harder to delimit and broader shoulders, thights and abs.
- Face is oval, as well as her rather large eyes, that take all her eyes sockets. She has a staring gaze with pupils going from light grey to dark grey. Eyesbrows are naturally frowned even when relaxed, giving her an unwelcoming attitude. Nose is straight, with a round shape at the end. Mouth is normal, with small lips, stained by blackberries based food. Teeth are not 100% straight and she has two or three facing teeth slightly overlaping. Natural dark circles around the eyes. Hair is dark and dense, often hides her ears, long enough to go just below collar bones.
- Voice is cranky and low. She is not speaking a lot, speaks more slowly than most people, in a very articulate way.

Floral attributes:

- Has a distinctive trait: most of her flowers were sprouted around her tailbone in the hope of her gaining more height with roots taking over the spine upside (normally sized children have sprouts located between the shoulder blades).
- Has 3 distinctive flowers: a carnivorus one (akin to Dionaea Muscipula) located in the back, a light emitting flower (akin to Lily of the Valley) and a decorative type of white lilies planted at the back of her neck, that sprouts on her skull. The carnivorous one was imposed to her, the light emitting one was a necessity for her to continue exploring some dark places, while the decorative one was choosen by herself for her pledge ceremony.

Character:

- Due to her survival lifestyle in the slums before she joined the order, which required discretion and intelligence, she is a fast learner with a determined, sometimes obsessive character, which can make her stubborness. She is not very talkative and not a very warm person, most people don't enjoy spending time with her and those close to her are also loners and off the charts people.
- An excellent pupil of the order, she excels at almost anything and is an honor student. She naturally expects people to be on her level and loses interest very fast in other people that can't follow her. She is respectful of superiors and masters both in the way she speaks and tone, but sometimes crosses the line and speaks her minds without anyone asking.
- She is strongly attached to her independance, despite joining the order and pleding allegence to a Flower Lord. She sees it as a mean of survival and a way of doing what she wants without having too many strings attached. She eventually wants to regain her full independance, which is not something that happens a lot.
- Does not feel happiness a lot. What makes her happy are some meals from when she was a kid, planting her tent in a quiet place and in the sun to feed her flowers, drawing and documenting her discoveries.
- Even if she can feel love and had a few partner, she is not very demonstraive and her character makes her a hard to follow lover.

Abilities:

- Extremely good at drawing and documenting discoveries. Her notebooks are among the most appreciated by the Order librarians.
- Excellent fighter, but she doesn't enjoy it and will, most of the time, try to avoid conflict through negociation.
- Ingenious and good at crafting, makes most of the tools she needs herself.

Weaknesses:

- Has a hard time understanding other people feelings.
- Bad at handling responsibilities.
- Harsh towards people who are on her side but not on her level.


Clothing and gear:

- Due to her allegence to the order and her Flower Lord, has to wear a large fabric collar around her neck, on which is attached with a metal chain ring the symbol of her Flower Lord.
- During the classes, wears the traditionnal unisex black clothes of the order. A large gow that hides most of the body with an opening to let flowers go through. The gow has a white collar that descends on the chest in two pans. The gow lenght stops mid calves. Students also wear black boots and, when going out black capes (to avoid strangers looking at them and protect their safety) and black gloves. They also have to wear a kind of nun's hat that hides their skull due to the decorative flowers growing on it, and scalpers wanting to steal and resell them. The hat covers the forehead with a fabric bandage, and is the source of a drape that goes on the skull. Depending on the type of flower, the hat can be more or less high. The whole hat stays in place with a strap that goes under the jaw and slightly covers the chin.
- During her missions, wears a close to the skin top that starts at her neck, goes under the shoulder and let the colarbones and shoulders free, and ends around her her waist. She also wears a special, leather made small armor at the end of her back and on her hips to protect her flowers when their are not needed. The armor is made of several striped of leather rounded on top of each other and can be opened by unfolding a lace. She had special tight trousers, with big pockets on the sides, with a strap that goes under the foot. She also wears big boots with reinforced leather to avoid spikes. Her hair is attached most of the time and she cuts her decorative sprouts very often.
- Her gear consists mostly of a big travel bag where she stores food supplies, notebooks, pens, plants, maps, shears, a vivarium. She also attachs saws on the outside for bigger cutting work.
- Most flower gatherers carry a dagger with them to defend themselves against wild animals and people. But when she discovers the chosen ones that are made of bramble wood, she orders a set of special saws that she can use in combat. Those saws come with a long wooded handle finished by two sided blade made of teeths. Contrary to traditionnal saws, they cut when they are pulled, not pushed, which allow her to place get close and retreat while doing damage when she fights.



====

NAME: Sublime Text Configuration
HOST: Knowledge
BREF: My Sublime Text configuration
PRIV: false
MENU: true
BODY:

# Sublime Text Configuration

 Sublime Text is a (link: https://www.sublimetext.com/ text: commercial source code editor). It natively supports many programming languages and markup languages. Users can expand its functionality with plugins, typically community-built and maintained under free-software licenses. To facilitate plugins, Sublime Text features a Python API.

Sublime Text had a lot of success with web developpers from around 2010 to 2016-2017. In 2015 Microsoft released Visual Studio Code, which quickly replaced Sublime Text as the editor of choice for the web developer crowd (including myself) due to its mix of text editor and IDE features.

Still after years of Visual Studio Code I recently came back to Sublime Text with the release of the fourth version in 2021. The main reasons are speed, quality of text rendering, aesthetics and workflow.

## My preferences

```
{
    "find_selected_text": true,
    "highlight_line": true,
    "hot_exit": false,
    "mini_diff": true,
    "show_git_status": true,
    "show_definitions": false,
    "trim_trailing_white_space_on_save": "all",
    "trim_only_modified_white_space": false,
    "word_wrap": true,
    "theme": "Adaptive.sublime-theme",
    "ignored_packages": [
        "Markdown",
        "Vintage",
    ],
    "color_scheme": "Mariana.sublime-color-scheme",
    "font_face": "Ibm Plex Mono",
    "font_size": 10.0,
    "line_padding_bottom": 1,
    "line_padding_top": 1,
    "auto_hide_menu": true,
    "dark_color_scheme": "Mariana.sublime-color-scheme",
    "light_color_scheme": "Celeste.sublime-color-scheme",
}
```

## My plugins

Sublime Text uses a plugin named _Package Control_ to install other plugins.

+ Open the Tools menu
+ Select Install Package Control…

Once it's install, use `ctrl + shift + p` and search for `Package Control: Install Package`. The packages I use:

? (link: https://github.com/sh4nks/sublime-text-plugin-autoclose text: Auto Close HTML Tags) : Closes HTML tags after a `>`.
? (link: https://github.com/liamcain/AutoFileName text: AutoFileName) : Autocompletes filenames.
? (link: https://facelessuser.github.io/BracketHighlighter/ text: BracketHilighter) : Hilights the corresponding brackets both in text and in the vertical line numbers column.
? (link: https://github.com/leonid-shevtsov/ClickableUrls_SublimeText text: Clickable URL) : Makes URLs in files clickable.
? (link: https://packagecontrol.io/packages/Color%20Highlighter text: Color Highlighter) : Shows colors inside the editor.
? (link: https://bitbucket.org/dougty/sublime-compare-side-by-side/src/master/ text: Compare Side by Side) : Allows to compare two files and automatically find the differences
? (link: https://github.com/spadgos/sublime-jsdocs text: DocBlockr) : Helps with writing documentation and code comments
? (link: https://emmet.io/ text: Emmet) : Helps creating snippets of HTML
? (link: https://github.com/jisaacks/GitGutter text: GitGutter) : Show information about the current Git Repository and last modifications
? (link: https://github.com/victorporof/Sublime-HTMLPrettify text: HTML/CSS/JS Prettify) : Code formater for HTML, CSS, JS and a few JS frameworks
? (link: https://sublimetext-markdown.github.io/MarkdownEditing/ text: Markdown Editing) : Syntax for markdown
? (link: https://github.com/tssajo/Minify text: Minify) : Minifies CSS, HTML, JavaScript, JSON or SVG files
? (link: https://packagecontrol.io/packages/Sass text: Sass) : Sass and SCSS support
? (link: https://github.com/benweier/Schemr text: Schemr) : Changes color and themes quickly
? (link: https://github.com/titoBouzout/SideBarEnhancements text: SideBarEnhancements) : Adds a lot of features to the sidebar when right clicking
? (link: https://sublimegit.readthedocs.io/en/latest/ text: SublimeGit) : Adds support for most Git actions
? (link: http://www.sublimelinter.com/en/stable/ text: SublimeLinter) : Adds linting to Sublime Text. Can then be combined with specific language linters like (link: https://github.com/SublimeLinter/SublimeLinter-csslint text: csslint) or (link: https://github.com/SublimeLinter/SublimeLinter-jshint text: jshint)
? (link: https://www.mfuentesg.dev/SyncSettings/ text: SyncSettings) : Allows to save Sublime Text settings and plugin list inside a Github Gist
? (link: https://packagecontrol.io/packages/Terminal text: Terminal) : Opens a terminal inside the current folder


